== Shrines of Kinomiya Faith == Notable shrines include: *'''{{ill|Kii Shrine|ja|紀伊神社|qq=draft}}''' (Hayakawa, Odawara, Kanagawa) – Formerly Kii-no-Miya/Kinomiya Daigongen, enshrining Itakeru-no-Mikoto and Prince Koretaka. *'''{{ill|Kibune Shrine (Manazuru)|ja|貴船神社 (真鶴町)|qq=draft}}''' (Manazuru, Ashigarashimo, Kanagawa) – Former district shrine known as Kimiyamiya Daimyōjin, enshrining Ōkuninushi, Kotoshironushi, and Sukunahikona. *'''{{ill|Kinomiya Shrine (Atami)|ja|来宮神社|qq=draft}}''' (Nishiyama, Atami, Shizuoka) – Former Village shrine, currently a {{ill|Beppyo Shrine|ja|別表神社|1=Beppyo Shrine|2=ja|3=別表神社|4=simple|5=Beppyo shrine|6=zh|7=別表神社|8=mr|9=बेप्प्यो तीर्थ|qq=draft}}, enshrining Itakeru-no-Mikoto. *'''{{ill|Kinomiya Shrine (Izushi Hachiman)|ja|来宮神社 (伊豆市八幡)|qq=draft}}''' (Izushi, Shizuoka) – Former district shrine, enshrining Itakeru-no-Mikoto. *'''{{ill|Hachimangu Kinomiya Shrine|ja|八幡宮来宮神社|qq=draft}}''' (Hachimanno, Itō, Shizuoka) – Former district shrine, Kinomiya Shrine merged into a {{ill|Hachiman Shrine|ja|八幡神|qq=draft}}, enshrining Iwakura Wake-no-Mikoto. *'''{{ill|Shiritaogi Shrine (Kinomiya Shrine)|ja|志理太乎宜神社|qq=draft}}''' (Shirata, Higashiizu, Shizuoka) – Former Village shrine, potential {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft}}, enshrining Itakeru-no-Mikoto. *'''{{ill|Kawazu Kinomiya Shrine|ja|川津来宮神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine|ja|杉桙別命神社|qq=draft}})''' (Tanaka, Kawazu, Shizuoka) – Shikinai-sha, former district shrine known as Kinomiya/Myōjin, enshrining Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto.
Additionally, many shrines within this area, while not explicitly named Kinomiya, also worship tree or driftwood deities and have unique abstinence rituals.
Historically, in the {{ill|Konan region of Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県#地域区分|qq=draft}} within {{ill|Shiga District, Ōmi Province|ja|滋賀郡|qq=draft}}, a practice called '''Kinomiya Shōjin''' (季宮精進) occurred specifically on {{ill|November 23 (lunar calendar)|ja|11月23日 (旧暦)|qq=draft}} to prevent fires by refraining from unnecessary fire usage and not consuming cooked food throughout the day. This practice is considered related to Kinomiya Faith<ref>『神道大辞典』, Heibonsha, 1937.</ref>.
