=User:Immanuelle/Kawazu Kinomiya Shrine|qq=}} ({{ill|Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine|ja|杉桙別命神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine|qq=}})''' (Tanaka, Kawazu, Shizuoka) – Shikinaisha, former district shrine known as Kinomiya/Myōjin, enshrining Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto.
Additionally, many shrines within this area, while not explicitly named Kinomiya, also worship tree or driftwood deities and have unique abstinence rituals.
Historically, in the {{ill|Konan region of Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県#地域区分|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konan region of Shiga Prefecture|qq=}} within {{ill|Shiga District, Ōmi Province|ja|滋賀郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiga District, Ōmi Province|qq=}}, a practice called '''Kinomiya Shōjin''' (季宮精進) occurred specifically on {{ill|November 23 (lunar calendar)|ja|11月23日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/November 23 (lunar calendar)|qq=}} to prevent fires by refraining from unnecessary fire usage and not consuming cooked food throughout the day. This practice is considered related to Kinomiya Faith<ref>『神道大辞典』, Heibonsha, 1937.</ref>.
